MAN: What's going on out there?

10:04.771 --> 10:06.398
[ALARM WAILING]

10:09.234 --> 10:10.360
Mayday! Mayday!

10:52.944 --> 10:56.073
MAN: The wolf and the
lamb shall feed together,

10:56.239 --> 10:59.539
and the lion shall eat
straw like the bullock,

10:59.701 --> 11:04.207
and dust shall be
the serpent's meat.

11:05.790 --> 11:09.590
All done, Evan Lee. You ready?

11:20.638 --> 11:23.391
EVAN LEE: God said,
"Let the earth bring forth"

11:23.558 --> 11:26.186
a living creature
after his kind.

11:28.313 --> 11:31.692
The cattle and the
creeping things

11:31.858 --> 11:35.863
"and the beasts of the
earth after his kind."

11:36.821 --> 11:38.823
And it was so.

11:40.158 --> 11:43.879
MAN: Let's go, Evan Lee.
Time to see the warden.

11:46.956 --> 11:53.054
Evan Lee, I'd like to get you to
reconsider speaking to the widow.

11:53.213 --> 11:56.683
It's just kind of best for
everybody if we just move on.

11:56.841 --> 11:59.936
The answer's still no.

12:00.094 --> 12:01.971
Well, now, you suit yourself.

12:02.138 --> 12:04.232
But tomorrow,
you're gonna be getting the needle.

12:04.390 --> 12:07.109
And if you really
believed in a hereafter

12:07.268 --> 12:09.191
and any kind of mercy there,

12:09.354 --> 12:11.356
go and give the widow
what she's asking for.

12:11.522 --> 12:14.275
I'm beyond mercy.

12:15.443 --> 12:18.037
- Get him out of here.
- Yes, sir.

12:18.446 --> 12:20.744
[THUNDER CRACKING]

12:28.915 --> 12:32.215
- Okay.
- Okay, what?

12:33.127 --> 12:34.845
Okay, you're right.

12:39.425 --> 12:41.928
It's time to make amends.

12:45.890 --> 12:47.062
JACKSON: Abe! - Over here.

12:47.225 --> 12:50.399
JACKSON: I can't find the pilot!
ABRAHAM: Keep looking.

13:13.543 --> 13:15.216
Come on.

13:19.090 --> 13:21.184
JACKSON: The pilot's gone.

13:26.639 --> 13:28.482
She not breathing?

13:31.352 --> 13:34.196
Don't stop. What are you doing?
What are you doing? Don't stop.

13:34.355 --> 13:36.107
- Jackson...
- Come on. Come on.

13:36.274 --> 13:37.742
Jackson. Jackson.

13:37.900 --> 13:39.072
- Come on. Come on.
- Jackson.

13:39.235 --> 13:41.033
Jackson!

13:54.751 --> 13:57.129
I still have no idea
what help I can be.

13:57.295 --> 13:59.673
I study patterns.
I process information.

13:59.839 --> 14:02.262
Your skill set is
exactly what I need.

14:02.425 --> 14:04.018
Those poor people
were attacked by dogs.

14:04.177 --> 14:06.100
Presume the attack was human.

14:06.262 --> 14:08.198
- This is ridiculous.
- Ridiculous? You mentioned that.

14:08.222 --> 14:10.520
Humor me.
Look with a different eye.

14:16.481 --> 14:20.486
The bodies in the morgue were in
various states of decomposition,

14:20.651 --> 14:22.870
indicating the attacks
took place over weeks.

14:25.281 --> 14:27.830
It is clear why the victims
weren't discovered for some time,

14:27.992 --> 14:29.494
but why were they not missed?

14:32.205 --> 14:34.299
Perhaps they were
targeted because

14:34.457 --> 14:36.425
they had few ties
to the community.

14:36.584 --> 14:38.211
For instance?

14:38.378 --> 14:40.301
Visitors.

14:41.464 --> 14:45.264
People without roots in the
city or the area. Tourists.

14:45.426 --> 14:47.849
Good. Anything else?

14:48.012 --> 14:50.561
It's a question of motive.

14:51.140 --> 14:54.690
If the victims were killed with no
possible gain to their killers...

14:54.852 --> 14:56.195
What?

14:56.354 --> 14:59.028
If we were dealing
with a human suspect.

14:59.190 --> 15:00.908
Multiple victims over time,

15:01.067 --> 15:03.991
murdered in a place where their
bodies wouldn't be discovered.

15:05.154 --> 15:07.873
There would only be one
possible explanation.

15:08.032 --> 15:10.956
- What is that?
- They're honing their skills.

15:11.119 --> 15:13.247
- Honing their skills?
- Yes.

15:13.413 --> 15:17.759
But why?
This was not humans but dogs.

15:17.917 --> 15:21.217
What purpose would it serve them
to be more efficient murderers?

15:21.379 --> 15:23.256
You do understand the problem.

15:24.298 --> 15:26.050
The question remains,

15:26.717 --> 15:29.470
are you willing to join me

15:29.637 --> 15:31.264
and do something about it?

15:38.563 --> 15:40.531
WOMAN: I'm sorry, miss,
I can't rent you a car

15:40.690 --> 15:42.170
because your credit
card is declined.

15:42.316 --> 15:43.863
Are you sure?

15:44.026 --> 15:45.869
- Could you try it again?
- Sure.

15:46.028 --> 15:48.702
Well, I knew the newspaper
biz was in the weeds,

15:48.865 --> 15:50.833
but getting a corporate
card knocked back...

15:50.992 --> 15:53.290
Actually,
now it's saying to cut up the card.

15:53.453 --> 15:56.172
No, no, no.
That That won't be necessary. Um...

15:57.665 --> 16:01.841
All right. Okay.
Suppose we can use one of mine.

16:02.003 --> 16:05.007
I'm sure The Telegraph
will reimburse me.

16:07.967 --> 16:09.014
Right?

16:11.554 --> 16:14.057
This trip has nothing to do
with The Telegraph, does it?

16:14.223 --> 16:16.851
It did. And then it didn't.

16:17.018 --> 16:18.986
Because I was fired.

16:19.645 --> 16:22.273
I spent my last 800 dollars
getting us here. I'm sorry.

16:22.440 --> 16:25.489
I know I shouldn't have lied to
you, but I did it for a good reason.

16:25.651 --> 16:27.028
Yeah.
That's the problem with you.

16:27.195 --> 16:29.289
Your "good reason"
barometer is on the fritz.

16:30.531 --> 16:32.374
Wait, where are you going?

16:32.533 --> 16:34.001
We have the meeting
with the senator.

16:34.160 --> 16:35.412
You have a meeting.

16:35.578 --> 16:37.125
I'm getting on the
next flight back.

16:37.288 --> 16:38.665
Call your guy at Caltech.

16:38.831 --> 16:41.129
Although, unlike me,
the guys at Caltech are smart.

16:41.292 --> 16:42.965
They're not gonna fall
for your ramblings.

16:43.127 --> 16:45.596
No, no. Wait, wait.
The flight doesn't leave for eight hours.

16:45.755 --> 16:48.634
Yeah, I'll get one of those chair massages.
A really long one.

16:48.799 --> 16:50.801
Or you could spend two
of those eight hours

16:50.968 --> 16:52.220
meeting the senator,

16:52.386 --> 16:56.266
laying out the findings
that could eventually lead

16:56.432 --> 16:59.060
to your securing a Nobel Prize.

16:59.977 --> 17:01.229
A Nobel Prize?

17:01.395 --> 17:03.523
Okay, maybe not a Nobel
Prize, but.

17:03.689 --> 17:05.907
But a different kind of prize.

17:06.067 --> 17:08.945
The kind of prize that makes you
feel really good about yourself.

17:12.949 --> 17:14.416
Come on, Mitch. Can l...?

17:14.575 --> 17:16.452
Can I at least show
you something first?

17:25.336 --> 17:28.886
The pilot sent an SOS
beacon on our way down.

17:29.048 --> 17:32.723
We can expect a rescue.
But who knows in how long.

17:35.388 --> 17:36.640
How do hundreds of bats

17:36.806 --> 17:39.776
fly 5,000 feet higher
than they normally do?

17:39.934 --> 17:41.186
Perhaps the radiation?

17:46.315 --> 17:49.489
How far do you think it is
to my father's compound?

17:49.652 --> 17:52.781
From the plane,
maybe three kilometers.

17:53.906 --> 17:56.455
We could make it there and
back before the rescue arrives.

17:56.617 --> 17:58.494
JACKSON: This thing
survived the crash.

17:58.661 --> 18:00.504
But I don't even know
what these numbers mean.

18:00.663 --> 18:02.290
Green.

18:03.124 --> 18:04.376
Maybe we're safe.

18:22.935 --> 18:26.485
EVAN LEE: "The wolf shall
also dwell with the lamb",

18:26.647 --> 18:30.242
and the leopard shall
lie down with the kid,

18:30.401 --> 18:35.623
and the calf and the young
lion and the fat/ing together,

18:35.781 --> 18:38.204
"and a little child
shall lead them."

18:38.367 --> 18:40.961
Ms. Blanchard, thank you for
taking the time to come down.

18:41.120 --> 18:43.794
I was surprised
to get your call.

18:45.374 --> 18:48.469
Well, most death row
inmates, in the end,

18:48.628 --> 18:51.097
they like to clear their
conscience before execution.

18:51.255 --> 18:53.098
I hadn't held out much
hope for Evan Lee,

18:53.257 --> 18:55.555
but, well, here we are.

19:05.394 --> 19:07.522
JACKSON: I can't
believe she's dead.

19:08.356 --> 19:10.905
Jackson, we did everything
we could for her.

19:11.067 --> 19:14.822
I know. But I would have
liked to have thanked her.

19:14.987 --> 19:17.240
For sticking by him.

19:17.823 --> 19:20.076
It's a hell of a lot more
than my mother and I did.

19:20.242 --> 19:22.620
Well,
from everything you told me,

19:22.787 --> 19:25.961
that was the best thing that
could have happened to all of you.

19:26.123 --> 19:29.047
But what if we were
wrong and he was right?

19:29.210 --> 19:32.180
Is it possible that we were
looking at the situation all wrong?

19:32.797 --> 19:34.845
What we thought was a
man on the edge of sanity

19:35.007 --> 19:38.011
was actually a man on the verge

19:38.177 --> 19:40.305
of an extraordinary
evolutionary breakthrough.

19:40.471 --> 19:44.317
Perception can
sometimes stain reality.

19:44.475 --> 19:47.729
That is why I don't tell
everybody about my past.

19:48.854 --> 19:50.447
We should keep going.

20:08.582 --> 20:10.880
I was 11 when my mom got sick.

20:11.043 --> 20:13.137
She was one of the first ones.

20:13.295 --> 20:15.297
Eventually, there were 26 more.

20:16.340 --> 20:20.470
Twenty-six formerly healthy
members of the community.

20:21.721 --> 20:23.018
Cancer clusters.

20:24.432 --> 20:27.060
JAMIE: We tried to make a case,

20:27.685 --> 20:29.733
but by then, Reiden was this

20:29.895 --> 20:31.772
huge,
monolithic super-corporation,

20:31.939 --> 20:34.442
and we were just a bunch of sick
farmers in a tidewater town.

20:37.570 --> 20:40.744
And who knows what causes
cancer, right?

20:42.908 --> 20:45.002
All you can do to avoid it...

20:45.828 --> 20:48.331
Are good luck and good genetics.

20:50.040 --> 20:51.838
